translation:
Dear Angel, why do you flee  
From me who tenderly loves you?  
You are the one, what do you think?  
In whom my soul finds delight;  
Lift your conquering eyes  
Upwards, show some compassion;  
I know your heart itself pleads for me.  
I will always watch for your favor,  
Even though you are averse,  
And always consider my duty:  
While I love you for eternity.  

2. Come, then, show your kindness  
Which is accompanied by sweetness.  
To me, you are my chosen one.  
Or am I not worthy of your favor?  
Since I pine for your love;  
Since I suffer a thousand pains;  
Since I languish because of your sigh and torment.  
Ah, I shall perish from love  
If I do not make you mine;  
Would you but lessen my pain;  
Make me stroke your bosom.  

3. Come then, Beauty, let us kiss,  
While it must be so sometime;  
Let us extinguish our flames  
In a chaste love’s fire;  
For even if you would drive me away,  
I would remain steadfast,  
Always loving, equally faithful.  
I will always be for you;  
For my heart never regrets;  
Even if you would not heal me,  
I would never leave you.

Ha, what grace that Steed has! } repeat.
(Cried a little boy:) look, oh look! }
Look, look! look, oh look!
Oh! let me try to ride it! } repeat.
I pray that this favor be granted to me. }
Look, look! look, oh look! }

Before you want to celebrate a foolish wish } repeat.
(Spoke the Rider:) test your strength! }
Wait, wait! wait! oh wait!
If you already want to manage a Horse, } repeat.
You risk your life thoughtlessly! }
Wait, wait! wait, oh wait! }

To You, who reigns in heaven, who governs the entire universe;  
To You, who crowns us with blessings, exalt Yourself, God!  
Before Your love, which already stood faithful,  
You have thought of us;  
Your care, which has shone for centuries, has always kept watch for us.

Infinite God! grant that we may give You honor! You,
who once spoke, and the whole universe existed;
Who lives eternally, and made all that lives live;
Who bound order and law with eternal bonds.
Infinite God! grant that we may give You honor! You,
who once spoke, and the whole universe existed;
Who lives eternally, and made all that lives live;
Who bound order and law with eternal bonds.

Hubbub! it pounds away merrily,  
Blacksmith! tell me, isn’t your arm getting tired?  
When we went to school this morning,  
You had already been forging and hammering for a long time;  
Oh! what work and sweating that is,  
Wait a moment, look around and have some rest!

- Mate! you don’t look that dumb yet,  
But you don’t understand a thing about forging;  
The iron is glowing, as you can see;  
Wait a bit, then it’s no good again;  
Remember, boys! it’s good that you know this:  
Iron that holds quality must be forged while glowing!

Almanac  
Liar  
Comes from Delft,  
Lies half;  
Comes from Aalsmeer,  
Lies even more;  
Comes from Dordt,  
Lies black;  
Comes from Zwartewaal,  
Lies about everything.

See, thus the gentlemen march,  
With their colorful clothes;  
See, thus the women march,  
With their wide sleeves;  
See, thus the young ladies march,  
With their beautiful slippers;  
See, thus the farmer rides,  
With his little horse behind;  
Ju, ju, we then say.

Boom, bam, Bavaria,  
Our kitty doesn’t like eggs;  
What does our kitty like then?  
Bacon in the pan;  
That makes our kitty fat.

There were seven little frogs,  
Already in a farmer's ditch;  
The ditch was frozen,  
The frogs half dead;  
They did not jump, they did not croak,  
From hunger and sorrow.

Alias  
Was in the cupboard;  
His mother thought it was the bread.

1. Above there rejoices a great multitude. Of children before God's throne, Delivered from sin and danger; To the honor of the Father's Son. {Now their song sounds: 'Praise be to the Lord, Who died on the cross'}

2. How did they come to that glorious place? They heard Jesus' voice, Believed in His precious Word, And gave their heart to Him. {Now their song sounds: 'Praise be to the Lord, Who died on the cross'}

3. They already heard here on earth The beloved Savior’s call, They loved Him and kept asking constantly: ‘What do You want me to do?' {Now their song sounds: 'Praise be to the Lord, Who died on the cross'}

4. They were sinful and unclean, Corrupted in spirit. But Jesus took them young and small And washed them in His blood. {Now their song sounds: 'Praise be to the Lord, Who died on the cross'}

5. We also wish to go there, To the place of joy and peace, Oh, dear Savior, accept us, Then we will sing eternally with: The heavenly song: ‘Praise be to the Lord, Who died on the cross’

1-5. ‘And in the heavenly Paradise, ‘A place for us acquired.’

1. Do not ask, O my heart, for joy from a day: the jubilation of the world, its sparkling smile. What it shows you as freedom and happiness brings you only danger for life and crown. Never build on the illusion of worldly splendor;

2. Do not thirst, O my heart, for wealth or fame; often the color of the most poisonous flower is beautiful. Wealth and power, if God did not give them to you, are chains and a forewarning of punishment. Never build on the illusion of worldly splendor;

3. Blessed, my heart, if in simplicity and quiet humility you conform to God's holy will, and in your striving are united with Jesus. You ripen for His life in the better land. Never build on the illusion of worldly splendor;

1-3. As because of the gold and jewel that adorn her, your heart fell unsuspecting into her snares, what can she give in exchange for your soul?

From ‘In the land of Alienation’.

1. That I belong to You—sister—a grateful heart is mine for it, It is my soul’s joy and life;  
2. Led by His gentle staff, I taste rest and blessedness, I hope for the joy of Heaven;  
3. Yes, my happiness it is and pride, That I may call You—sister—Shepherd, One of His own may know me;  
1. He has given me His Name, Pledged me His holy blood For my arrival in the Father’s land.  
2. What once delighted me before Is now known in salvation’s good, Spirit torment and misery.  
3. Could You, Lord! forget my heart, Stronger than my heart are You, You who live and reign in me.

1. Bird - line, do you hear how one beckons enticingly in the woods with a whistle?  
2. Be wise, do not feast on the bush that glows there;  
3. Birdservant, it is a bait, a senselessly set trap;  
4. Ah, it still allows itself to be seduced, the little louse does not listen to good advice;  
1. Do not allow yourself, I pray, to be seduced by that wonderfully sweet sound!  
2. For your life, dear little creature, is surely at risk because of it!  
3. Quickly, go in another direction, back to your nest at this moment!  
4. It is now certainly caught quickly, and then regret comes too late!

Father hums: 'Working, toiling  
Makes me a strong man;  
It brings us prosperity, it gives pleasure;  
That is why I work as much as I can!'

Mother whispers: 'Loving, caring  
Is a blessing and a comfort to me;  
It makes the work light, it strengthens the spirit;  
That is why I love husband and children.'

Father hums, mother whispers,  
Always equally free and happy;  
I have overheard their song,  
I love and work now just like they do!

I have a hobby horse  
With a flaxen tail;  
It has a bridle around the wooden head,  
I ride it all day long;  
E. van Offel  
I ride it to the farthest land,  
I lead it with my quick mind;  
Hopsasa!  
That is fun!  
I make it turn, twist,  
Trot, gallop;  
Just like a general:  
Straight and proud on horseback!  
I wear a pointed hat, proud and happy,  
And a saber at my side;  
Hopsasa!  
Admire me!

Let the wind blow,  
I will swing my saber;  
I wildly fling it in the air,  
So the bird is startled and flees;  
If my steed doesn't go well,  
I pull it by the tail a bit;  
Hopsasa!  
Forward, my horse.

Just let me be,  
The horse will indeed move;  
I hold the reins firmly,  
So the beast won't surprise me.  
I call now "gee!" and then "whoa!"  
I bob, swing, free and merry;  
Hopsasa!  
Who can do that like this?

Fetching two buckets of water, / Pumping two buckets Girls on clogs, girls on their wooden leg, just ride through my little street.  
From your ras ras ras the king rides through the puddle,  
from your voort voort voort the king rides through the gate,  
from your erk erk erk the king rides to the church,  
from your one two three.

1. Children, stop your work with me  
Do you hear the bell from that church over there  
Kling klang kling klang kling  
) How sweet that sounds  
)  2x  
Ave Maria, O hail to you

Sleep, little child, sleep;  
your father has a little lamb;  
and it already has white feet,  
and it drinks the milk so sweetly;  
it drinks the milk until its belly is full,  
and it sleeps like a mole.  
So, so little child, so, so,  
sleep and close your little eyes;  
if you are not tired, you must not sleep,  
if you are not hungry, you must not yawn,  
so, so little child, so, so,  
sleep and close your little eyes.

Sleep, little child, sleep;  
your father has a little lamb;  
and it already has white feet,  
and it drinks the milk so sweetly;  
it drinks the milk until its belly is full,  
and it sleeps like a mole.  
Then, then little child, then, then,  
sleep and close your little eyes;  
if you are not tired, you should not sleep,  
if you are not hungry, you should not yawn,  
then, then little child, then, then,  
sleep and close your little eyes.

Lovers who truly bind you together with love;  
I do ask you to consider well?  
What is it that you are beginning;  
It is neither an ox nor a cow to buy,  
Nor is it a child’s game;  
But it is already quite a firmer knot;  
So consider it well.  
It is not yet, dearest, time to go to bed,  
Nor butter on the tree,  
But care that worries do not prevent you,

In the morning when he came to wake me,  
With the crowing of the day;  
He came to pull at my window:  
While I was still lying in my rest;  
And I said I praised my love, bis.  
Then open your door for me;  
For the day has already risen,  
Then hurry to me as well.

When the first couple joined together,  
In Eden’s flowery garden decided,  
No celebratory horn yet sounded around;  
For behold! it had no banquet companions.  
Then, the feathered creature did not remain silent,  
And came to crown this marriage with praise;  
Yes, it sang a striking wedding song,  
To show the joyful couple its happiness, bis.

The field was the green wedding table,  
On which no cook displayed his skill;  
There was found neither roast nor fish,  
But the tasty east from woods and valleys;  
Clear water flowed instead of wine;  
Yet love was allowed to crown the celebration:  
One can be joyful with little,  
If love and joy dwell in the heart. bis.

Let us with joyful singing sound,  
In honor of Bridegroom and Bride,  
Celebrate this feast of love;

I am happily at my work again;  
ha; ha;  
And make the shoes neat and strong,  
ha; ha;  
Through which my boss gains many customers,  
And I steadily find work.  
ha; ha; ha; etc.

A working man must be active.  
ha; ha;  
I make no Monday or Krispin,  
ha; ha;  
But work hard through the whole week,  
And thus fulfill my duty.  
ha; ha; ha;  
Diligence, that beautiful virtue,  
ha; ha;  
Provides us money and gives us joy,  
ha; ha;  
Laziness is what causes pain,  
Covering man with the garment of poverty.  
ha; ha; ha;

That he who likes it, makes a Monday.  
ha; ha;  
I have no taste for idleness;  
ha; ha;  
Nor do I then feel any self-reproach,  
For wasting of the precious time.  
ha, ha; ha;

My mates! who do not work today,  
ha; ha;  
But now sit with Fat Peter,  
ha; ha;  
Like gentlemen at their tipple,  
And think of no Saturday.  
ha; ha; ha;

They each have a grievance:  
ha; ha;  
That is: the money dances in their pocket,  
ha; ha;  
And it must, down to the last penny,  
Be spent on Monday before evening.  
ha; ha; ha;  
By Tuesday their head is bare;  
ha; ha;  
Because they have drunk too much,  
ha; ha;  
Work has no appeal at all;  
They droop and sleep and seem quite mad.  
ha; ha; ha;

So already two days are lost;  
ha; ha;  
But Wednesday then one works stoutly;  
ha; ha;  
Yet however one strives and toils,  
The week is short and not going well.  
ha; ha; ha;

On Saturday then one looks worried,  
ha; ha;  
While I receive the most money then.  
ha; ha;  
And because their week is always scant,  
I provide them to their annoyance.  
ha; ha; ha;

And when one comes home to his wife,  
ha; ha;  
One spins her a yarn,  
ha; ha;  
As if the work did not go smoothly;  
Thus the good worker is deceived.  
ha; ha; ha;  
If the received money is then  
Counted purely for the wife;  
ha; ha;  
But no; she does not get it all,  
Some of it is skimmed off through the throat.  
ha; ha; ha;

The woman sighs, but it does no good,  
ha; ha;  
The week is bad, just as she sees.  
ha; ha;  
And while she grumbles and moans about it,  
She falls very short of money that week.  
ha; ha; ha;

Whereas it was only this week alone,  
ha; ha;  
That still got by somehow.  
ha; ha;  
But alas; most are still worse off;  
Thus the woman eventually knows no advice.  
ha; ha; ha;

However she turns or twists the matter;  
ha; ha;  
It is poverty from beginning to end.  
ha; ha;  
Thus one works toward his misfortune,  
Casting wife and children into distress.  
ha; ha; ha;  
A working man has enough work.  
ha; ha;  
Even if he does not squander the money in the tavern,  
ha; ha;  
That he lives by the sweat of his face.  
And each gives to his own.  
ha; ha; ha;

You see in me a chamberlain;  
I serve a noble lady.  
She is steadily revered by me;  
I also perform my work, so I believe,  
Faithfully fulfilling my duty.  

It is true, much is required:  
Much skill, a pure mind,  
Courtesy, modesty, and taste;  
But with a good will, our efforts are often  
Richly rewarded.
